r this edition, Bettina Aptheker has provided an introduction that revisits crucial events of the late 1960s and early 1970s and puts Davis's case into the context of that time and our own—from the killings at Kent State and Jackson State to the politics of the prison system today. This book gives a first-hand account of the worldwide movement for Angela Davis's freedom and of her trial. It offers a unique historical perspective on the case and its continuing significance in the contemporary political landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aTrials (Conspiracy)zCaliforniazSan Jose. 4aGender Studies. 4aU.S. History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh1 aAptheker, Bettina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147014140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470141423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801470141/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles